'''[[Polygamy]] in [[Morocco]]''' is legal,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mbctimes.com/english/life/polygamy-how-moroccans-trick-to-have-a-second-wife |title=Polygamy: How Moroccans trick to have a second wife |last=Medini |first=Mona |date=January 23, 2015 |publisher=MBC Times |access-date=November 25, 2016 |quote=[Polygamy] legally becomes theoretically almost impossible if not completely impossible.}}</ref> but very uncommon due to restrictions that were introduced by the [[Moroccan government|government]] in 2004 that mandated financial qualifications a [[husband]] must meet in order to marry a second wife.<ref name=Mor1>{{cite web |url=https://www.moroccoworldnews.com/2014/05/130885/morocco-polygamous-man-arrested-on-night-of-his-second-wedding/ |title=Morocco: Polygamous Man Arrested on night of His Second Wedding |last=Geneva |first=Erin |date=May 17, 2014 |publisher=Morocco World News |access-date=November 25, 2016 |quote=Legally, no man may take a second wife without the permission of the first wife, as well as making a case to a judge that he is financially able to support both wives, and their children equally, and that his circumstances are exceptional.}}</ref> In addition, a husband must have written permission from his current wife before marrying a second wife.<ref name=Mor1 /> Breaking these rules and marrying without permission from one's current wife can and has resulted in arrests.<ref name=Mor1 />

