{{Infobox women by region | image = Czech Girl in Prague.jpg | caption = A portrait of a young modern-day woman in [[Prague]], the Czech Republic | gii = 0.087 (2013) | gii_rank = 13th out of 152 | gii_ref = <ref name=gii>{{cite web|title=Table 4: Gender Inequality Index|url=http://hdr.undp.org/en/content/table-4-gender-inequality-index|publisher=United Nations Development Programme|accessdate=7 November 2014}}</ref> | matdeath = 5 (2010) | womparl = 20.6% (2013) | femed = 99.9% (2012) | womlab = 64.4% ([[employment rate]] [[OECD]] definition, 2016)<ref>http://stats.oecd.org/Index.aspx?DatasetCode=LFS_SEXAGE_I_R#</ref> | ggg = 0.6770 (2013) | ggg_rank = 83rd | ggg_ref = <ref name="ggr">{{cite web|title=The Global Gender Gap Report 2013|url=http://www3.weforum.org/docs/WEF_GenderGap_Report_2013.pdf#page=20|publisher=World Economic Forum|pages=12–13}}</ref> }} {{Women in society sidebar}} The history, characteristic, evolution, and [[genealogy|genealogies]] of present-day '''women in the Czech Republic''' can be traced back from many centuries before the establishment of the country now known as the [[Czech Republic]]. They have originated from ancestral [[Slavs|Slavic settlers]] who had an economy that was based primarily on agriculture.<ref>{{cite web|title=Czech Republic - HISTORY|url=http://www.mongabay.com/reference/country_studies/czech-republic/HISTORY.html|publisher=Mongabay.com|accessdate=6 November 2013}}</ref> After the period in the [[history of the Czech Republic]] known as the [[Velvet Revolution]], many women have become individuals with full-time jobs and who, at the same time, are also focusing on their responsibilities as homemakers, giving themselves "a high sense of personal efficacy and independence" within [[Czechs|Czech society]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Ferber|first=Marianne A. and Phyllis Hutton Raabe|title=Women in the Czech Republic: Feminism, Czech Style|url=https://www.jstor.org/discover/10.2307/20020174?uid=3739256&uid=2&uid=4&sid=21102874243127|work=International Journal of Politics, Culture, and Society Vol. 16, No. 3, Toward Gender Equity: Policies and Strategies (Spring, 2003), pp. 407-430|publisher=JSTOR, Springer|accessdate=6 November 2013}}</ref>
==Reproductive rights and family life== The [[maternal mortality]] rate in Czech Republic is 5 deaths/100,000 live births (as of 2010).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/rankorder/2223rank.html|title=The World Factbook|work=cia.gov|accessdate=17 June 2016}}</ref> The [[HIV/AIDS]] rate is 0.05% of adults (aged 15–49) - estimates of 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/rankorder/2155rank.html|title=The World Factbook|work=cia.gov|accessdate=17 June 2016}}</ref> The [[total fertility rate]] (TFR) is 1.43 children born/woman (2014 estimates), one of the lowest in the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/rankorder/2127rank.html|title=The World Factbook|work=cia.gov|accessdate=17 June 2016}}</ref> As in many other European countries, family formation has become more liberal, [[cohabitation|unmarried cohabitation]] has increased and the connection between fertility and [[marriage]] has decreased in the past decades; as of 2017, 49% of births were to unmarried women.<ref>https://www.czso.cz/csu/czso/ari/population-change-year-2017</ref>
==Education== Czech Republic has a very high [[literacy rate]], which is the same for women and men at 99% (estimates of 2011).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/fields/2103.html|title=The World Factbook|work=cia.gov|accessdate=17 June 2016}}</ref> However more men (95%) than women (90%) have completed high-school ([[OECD]] 2014).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oecdbetterlifeindex.org/countries/czech-republic/|title=OECD Better Life Index|work=oecdbetterlifeindex.org|accessdate=17 June 2016}}</ref>
